Create a data frame called area whose columns are state, farm, and land, which contain state names, farm areas, and land areas, respectively. Hint: the states arent in the same order in the two data sets, so getting the area data frame right requires a little care.

tables <- tables[-51, ]

The two outliers are Texas, which fits the roughly linear trend of the rest of the data, and Alaska, which does not fit.

Make a linear model of y = farm area vs.x = land area. Make your scatterplot again, and this time add the regression line to it. Then make a linear model of the same data, except with Alaska removed. Add that regression line, colored red, to your scatterplot.

fit.area <- lm(farm ~ land, data = area)
plot(x = area$land, y = area$farm, xlab = "Land Area (sq. mi)", ylab = "Farm Area (sq. mile)")
abline(fit.area)
fit.area.noalaska <- lm(farm ~ land, data = area[-outlier.2, ])
abline(fit.area.noalaska, col = "red")

Notice that, with respect to the original regression line, Texas has the biggest residual (difference in actual and predicted y), because Alaska pulled the line down toward itself. But really Alaska is the outlier! Next well do a jackknife procedure to discover computationally that Alaska is the most important outlier.

Make a plot of the residuals for the original model. (Hint: theyre available in the output of lm().)

plot(fit.area, which = 1)

Notice again that the Texas residual is bigger than the Alaska residual.

Next use a loop to create n=50 models. In step i, make a model of the data with observation i removed. Then predict the value of y[i] from that model, and find the residual (difference) between (the removed) y[i] and the prediction. Save these residuals in a vector r.jack. (A jackknife procedure works by removing one observation (or several) from a data set, and then making a prediction from that smaller data set, and repeating this for each observation.)

r.jack <- data.frame(residuals = numeric())
for (i in 1:dim(area)[1]) {
  fit.area.jack <- lm(farm ~ land, data = area[-i, ])
  pred <- predict(fit.area.jack, newdata = data.frame(land = area$land[i]))
  resid.jack <- area$farm[i] - pred
  r.jack <- rbind(r.jack, resid.jack)
}

Plot these jackknife residuals.

plot(x = predict(fit.area), y = r.jack$X.12031.1567752233, xlab = "Fitted Values for Original Linear Model", ylab = "Jackknife Residuals", ylim = c(-400000, 400000))
abline(h = 0, lty = 2)

Notice now that Alaska is clearly the real outlier.

  1. Old Faithful is a geyser in Yellowstone National Park that erupts on a remarkably regular schedule (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Faithful). Make a scatterplot of waiting time (\(y\)) vs.most recent eruption time (\(x)\) from the built-in faithful data set. (See ?faithful.) Include a simple linear regression line. What is the most striking feature of this plot?
ggplot(faithful, aes(x = eruptions, y = waiting)) +
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

The most striking feature of the the plot is the grouping of the data. When the eruption time is greater than about 4 minutes the waiting time tends to be above 70 minutes. However, when the eruption time is less than 3 minutes the waiting time tends to be below 70 minutes.
